WE CLAIM

1. A processor-implemented method comprising:

receiving, via an input/output (I/O) interface, a plurality of medical predictions (d) from one or more doctor agents, a ground truth and a structured reasoning (t) of the plurality of medical predictions;

processing, via one or more hardware processors, the received plurality of medical predictions (d) using a pretrained test safety agent to analyze at least one of (i) a redundant diagnostic test, and (ii) a high-risk diagnostic test to determine test safety alert;

analyzing, via the one or more hardware processors, the received plurality of medical predictions (d) using a pretrained prescription safety agent to determine one or more unsafe prescriptions, wherein the pretrained prescription safety agent verifies violation of at least one of (i) contraindication, and (ii) drug-drug interaction (DDI) rules;

computing, via the one or more hardware processors, an Operational Safety Index (OSI) based on the determined test safety alert and the determined one or more unsafe prescriptions;

measuring, via the one or more hardware processors, an epistemic uncertainty by analyzing each of the plurality of medical predictions independently by each of the one or more doctor agent to compute a consensus disagreement rate (CDR), wherein the CDR is computed as:

