wherein ğ‘“(ğ‘‘) represents one or more doctor agents predicting diagnosis (d) for case (i) and ğ¾ is the total number of doctor agents;

analyzing, via the one or more hardware processors, the received structured reasoning (t) of the plurality of medical predictions to compute a Reasoning-Diagnosis Consistency (RDC) based on a cosine similarity, wherein the cosine similarity is calculated between sentence embeddings of the structured reasoning (t) and a final diagnosis;

computing, via the one or more hardware processors, an Epistemic Trust Index (ETI) based on the computed CDR, RDC, and an accuracy, wherein the ETI is represented as:

determining, via the one or more hardware processors, a Final Trust Index (FTI) by integrating the computed ETI and the computed OSI, wherein the FTI is represented as:

FTI=0.5Ã—ETI+0.5Ã—OSI

2. The processor-implemented method of claim 1, wherein the plurality of medical predictions (d) comprising a set of prescriptions for medication and diagnostic test.

3. The processor-implemented method of claim 1, wherein the structured reasoning (t) comprising at least one of (i) intermediate hypotheses and their supporting evidence, (ii) motivations for diagnostic test orders, and (iii) discarded hypotheses with rationales from one or more doctor agents.

4. A system (100) comprising:

a memory (110) storing instructions;

one or more Input/Output (I/O) interfaces (104); and

one or more hardware processors (108) coupled to the memory (110) via the one or more I/O interfaces (104), wherein the one or more hardware processors (108) are configured by the instructions to:

receive a plurality of medical predictions (d) from one or more doctor agents, a ground truth and a structured reasoning (t) of the plurality of medical predictions;

process the received plurality of medical predictions (d) using a pretrained test safety agent to analyze at least one of (i) a redundant diagnostic test, and (ii) a high-risk diagnostic test to determine test safety alert;

analyze the received plurality of medical predictions (d) using a pretrained prescription safety agent to determine one or more unsafe prescriptions, wherein the pretrained prescription safety agent verifies violation of at least one of (i) contraindication, and (ii) drug-drug interaction (DDI) rules;

compute an Operational Safety Index (OSI) based on the determined test safety alert and the determined one or more unsafe prescriptions;

measure an epistemic uncertainty by analyzing each of the plurality of medical predictions independently by each of the one or more doctor agent to compute a consensus disagreement rate (CDR), wherein the CDR is computed as:

